I am significantly revising down my expectations based on the trends in the index over the last three months (thank you @nigster for your ongoing calculations [1]). The index peaked towards the end of 2018, and inflation rates have continued to fall. I remain confused by the gap between the Bloomberg index inflation rates (<50k%) and other reports putting inflation at over 250k% [2] or even closer to 10 million [3]. While the levels vary vastly, all reports suggests that inflation has come down since the spring. So, it seems unlikely that the price of coffee will shoot up to over 25,000 bolivars to make even the second bucket (50-100k %) in the next six weeks.

Inflation seems to have peaked, but is still at extreme highs. M2 has grown but the growth rate in M2 has fallen as well. I dont expect the inflation to level off just yet, they are still in massive problems, namely the deterioation in their oil industry is still crushing their economy. According to the study on hyperinflation "On the Measurement of Zimbabwe’s Hyperinflation" they conclude that the average hyperinflation period is around 20 months. Mind you with huge uncertainty given the very little data i.e. about 25-30 hyperinflation incidences in the 21st and 20th century and with uncertainty in gathering data. According to the con leche index, hyperinflation "began" around november 2018 - december 2018, given that the price doubled from 195 to 400 bolivars, a rapid increase. That is about 6-7 months of hyperinflation, vastly less than the average hyperinflation period of 20 months. Furthermore, even if inflation did suddenly drop to 1-2% per month, the annual inflation would still be higher. Thus, for the annual inflation rate to become less than 50,000%, we need to go from hyperinflation to deflation, which i dont believe is impossible but highly unlikely. The trend in annual inflation rate is slowing down, thus, i do think that it will grow, but i dont think it will in a matter of a few months grow beyond 100,000%. It is quite likely it does, but the most likely scenario given the current trend, the lower growth in M2 i expect inflation to be between 50,000-100,000% by september. 100,000-200,000 will be my next most likely scenario and will have the highest probability. My probability estimates for each "category" will be weighted with the crowd estimates - EDIT: I did weight the estimates, but the estimates where i had highest conviction i put more emphasis on my own perception than the crowd, giving more weight to my own estimate.

I was planning on getting in to some reading on historical limits of hyperinflation, and a general vibe of the political situation and chances of change in the next 12 weeks. But I'm making my prediction without that - because simply looking at the numbers would make >50,000% almost impossible.

The time frame of the question is from 26 Sept 2018 to 25 Sept 2019 and at the start of that period the price of a single cup of coffee at Cafe Con Leche was 50 bolívars, therefore the bucket boundaries for the price of a coffee on 25 Sept 2019 are;

This index roughly looks like a yoy price change of a cup of Cafe Con Leche (right now its 5500, compared to 6 a year ago or the 91567%). By Sep 25 of last year, that cup has risen to 50 Bolivars. If the price stays below 25000 in the next 3 months (i.e. ~5x) then the <50k % will win. Similarly, if it goes to 25-50k, then the 2nd option would be correct.

Due to this I’ll put most of my confidence say 75% in the under 50k% bin with decreasing amounts in higher bins.

According to Bloomberg's Café con Leche index, the cost of a café con leche increased from 5.50 bolivars on June 6, 2018 to 5,500 bolivars (an increase of 99,900 percent) as of June 6, 2019. It is very likely that the inflation rate will continue to increase given that the economic crisis is ongoing and little has been done to abate it. However, the price of a café con leche has remained at 5,500 for 5 weeks now, which is the longest a price has remained stable in the past year. In addition, further developments involving Juan Guaido may cause regime change or help strengthen the markers. However, it is very unlikely that the inflation rate will drop below 100,000 percent or exceed 200,000 percent within the next three months.

Getting inflation under control in Venezuela is likely to require the involvement of the international community, and yet the international community seems to be distancing themselves from the Maduro government. So, any plan to address hyperinflation is likely to require a change in leadership, with a plan taking at least a few months to implement. The crowd forecast for a Maduro departure by the end of September 2019 is currently at 16% [1]. Given the lead time to implement a plan, I've discounted the chance of bringing inflation under control (< 50k%) to 10%.

According to Austrian Economics, inflation is the rate at fiat-money is increasing in the economy. For other economic schools, it measures the devaluation of money. Having this concept in mind, Venezuela's government can keep on printing money to sustain it's expenses for some time. If there is no political change, the rate of inflation might be somewhat around the recent months, witch is higher than 2018 numbers. So, we expect a higher inflation for 2019.
